indicator.name: Annual wages for select wage groups

indicator_meta.value: Annual wage incomes for the top 1%, bottom 90%, and other wage groups, with particular focus on the highest wage earners.

The CEO pay ratio is average annual CEO compensation divided by average private-sector production and nonsupervisory worker compensation (measured as wages and benefits on a full-time, full-year basis).
Average hourly wages of all wage and salary workers from the Current Population Survey Outgoing Rotation Group.
Median hourly wages of all wage and salary workers from the Current Population Survey Outgoing Rotation Group.

Average hourly earnings of all private-sector employees and production and non-supervisory employees by industry and geographic area using the Bureau of Labor Statistics Current Employment Statistics survey.
Total private

Wage percentiles are wages at distinct points in the wage distribution. The 90-10, 90-50, and 50-10 wage ratios show how much greater wages are at the top than at the bottom, at the top than at the middle, and at the middle than at the bottom, respectively.
Wage percentiles at distinct points in the wage distribution by demographic groups and geographic region.
The Black-white wage gap is the percent by which hourly wages of Black workers are less than hourly wages of white workers. Overall and gender-specific Black-white gaps are available.
The gender wage gap is the percent by which hourly wages of female workers are less than hourly wages of male workers. Overall and race-specific gender wage gaps are available.
The Hispanic-white wage gap is the percent by which hourly wages of Hispanic workers are less than hourly wages of white workers. Overall and gender-specific Hispanic-white gaps are available.
The college wage premium is the percent by which hourly wages of four-year college graduates exceed those of high school graduates. Overall and gender-specific college wage premium are available.
Average annual weeks and hours worked by wage and salary workers using data from the Current Population Survey Annual Social and Economic Supplements

The number of employed people, the employment-to-population ratio (the share of the civilian noninstitutional population that is employed), and the distributional shares of employment by demographic groups and geographic region.

The number of labor force participants, the labor force participation rate (the share of the civilian noninstitutional population that is working or looking for work), and the distributional shares of the labor force, by demographic groups and geographic region.

The number of long-term unemployed people and the long-term unemployment rate (the share of the labor force that has been unemployed for six months or longer), by demographic groups and geographic region.
The number of people with multiple jobs and the share of the employed holding multiple jobs, by demographic groups and geographic region.
The total number of employees and number of production and non-supervisory employees, by industry and state, from the Bureau of Labor Statistics Current Employment Statistics data.
Total nonfarm
The number of part-time employees and the share of part-time workers in total employment, by demographic groups and geographic region.
The number of employees reporting they are working part-time for economic reasons, and the share of those workers in total employment, by demographic group and geographic region.

Underemployed workers are either 1) unemployed, 2) working part time but want and are available to work full time (an involuntary part timer), or 3) want and are available to work and have looked for work in the last year but have given up actively seeking work in the last four weeks (marginally attached worker).
The number of unemployed people, the unemployment rate (the share of the labor force that is unemployed), and the distributional shares of the unemployed, by demographic groups and geographic region.
The nominal minimum wage is the hourly minimum wage set by federal law. The real minimum wage is the federal hourly minimum wage adjusted for inflation.
The number and distributional shares of the civilian, non-institutional population, ages 16 and above, by demographic group and geographic region.
The number and distributional shares of the working age population (1664), by demographic group and geographic region.
The economically insecure population are those ages 16-64, not enrolled in education, and that live in families with income less than 200% of the federal poverty rate
The number and share of people who live in families with money incomes below their poverty threshold, by demographic groups and geographic region. Based on American Community Survey data.

The number and share of people who live in families with money incomes below their poverty threshold, by demographic groups and geographic region. Based on Current Population Survey Annual Social and Economic Supplement data.
The number and share of people who live in families with total resources below their Supplemental Poverty Measure threshold, by demographic groups and geographic region.
Price indexes measure how high prices are relative to some reference period and form the basis for measuring inflation rates.
Annual and year-to-year inflation rates for price indexes like the BLS Chained Consumer Price Index (C-CPI-U) and the BEA Personal Consumption Expenditures (PCE) index.
Productivity and pay indexes are measured as economy-wide net productivity and average production/non-supervisory compensation, relative to 1948 levels.

Productivity is how much workers produce per hour: total economic output, minus depreciation, divided by economy-wide hours worked. Pay is measured as average wage and nonwage compensation for production and nonsupervisory workers.
The number and share of union members and those represented by a union, by demographic groups, geographic region, and sector.
The union wage premium is the percent by which hourly wages of union workers exceeds hourly wages of similar non-union workers. Available by demographic groups.
The share of union members at the national level since 1917.

The teacher pay gap is the percent difference between the weekly wages of public school teachers and other similar college graduates. The regression-based gap controls for systematic differences in factors that otherwise determine pay, including age, education, marital status, race/ethnicity, and state of residence. Available by gender.
